{"type":"message","id":"42feaf65","parentId":"018548bf","timestamp":"2026-04-29T16:18:37.452Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the full picture. The cron job at 12:09 PM ran with these steps:\n1. It read `last_icloud_id.txt` which returned \"0\" (didn't exist → defaulted to \"0\")\n2. It listed ALL iCloud emails (IDs 6-11)\n3. It reported all of them because \"ID > 0\"\n4. It updated `last_icloud_id.txt` to \"11\"\n\nThe cron at 11:09 AM also read the file and got \"11\" as the last seen ID. Then at 12:09 PM, it got \"0\" again (because the file didn't exist or was reset to 0 by something).\n \nSo the core problem is that `last_icloud_id.txt` keeps getting reset to \"0\" between cron runs, either because the file is missing or something is zeroing it out. When the file shows \"11\" at 11:09 AM, the cron correctly skips those emails, but then a few hours later it reverts to \"0\" and they're all flagged as new again.\n\nI need to trace back where this reset is happening—it could be in a Python script or cron configuration that got modified.\n","thinkingSignature":"8467a1d22b6baecee7a78e777295861dab130221b6211e9011633c49b69825e4"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_4tjh56aygza3_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -r \"last_icloud\\|icloud_id\" ~/.openclaw/workspace-emmy/*.py ~/.openclaw/workspace-emmy/*.sh 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":1719,"output":306,"cacheRead":56896,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":58921,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777479512162,"responseId":"06416258cbf6cb54218a6b0d403bf772"}}
