{"type":"message","id":"dd929d79","parentId":"e4178d48","timestamp":"2026-04-29T16:18:45.298Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No script files reference `last_icloud_id`. This means the cron job instructions are embedded in the cron message itself, not in a separate script. Let me now understand the full picture:\n\n1. The cron job `449f0d3e` runs hourly and fetches an inline instruction set\n2. The instruction says to read `last_icloud_id.txt` and only report emails where `ID > last_seen_ID`\n3. BUT - the 12:10 PM run (fb7f6b6b) said `last_icloud_id.txt` returned \"0\", which means the file didn't exist → last_seen_ID = 0\n4. When last_seen_ID = 0, all emails with ID > 0 (ALL 6 emails IDs 6-11) get reported\n\n\n5. The 11:09 AM run (0ae98548) read the file and found it contained \"11\" already, but then overwrote it with \"11\" again\n\nThe real problem is that `last_icloud_id.txt` started at \"0\" and was never properly initialized before the first run reported all those old emails. The 12:10 PM run repeated the same mistake by setting it back to \"0\" and reporting everything again.\n\nNow I see it clearly: when the file was missing both times, it echoed \"0\" as the default, which triggered reporting of all 6 emails each time instead of just the new ones. The file should never have been \"0\" in the first place—it either existed with the actual last processed ID, or it shouldn't exist at all so the first run knows to treat all emails as new.\n","thinkingSignature":"fb41e4175460f116603c3f888c3ec19f6abed0b40149b3365125197e76b90c74"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_l60ge53wrvqh_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"stat ~/.openclaw/workspace-emmy/last_icloud_id.txt 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":100,"output":386,"cacheRead":58592,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":59078,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"sto