{"type":"message","id":"1af8ad00","parentId":"d15bef46","timestamp":"2026-04-29T23:03:35.997Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The code was already used (it's a one-time use auth code). Google OAuth codes can only be used once. We need a fresh auth code from the browser.\n\nThe page redirected to localhost which Chrome couldn't reach. But the code IS in the URL - `4/0AeoWuM-E82Qv1bh2sOHlChYlxYByHLBI6gbYu2gv10vNQSysxARNSRYOQsqe52-1H14-XA` was the code shown in the URL. But it's already been used (the first exchange succeeded, the second failed with invalid_grant because code already consumed).\n \nThe first exchange actually returned tokens successfully - I got an access token and refresh token back. So the code was consumed in that initial exchange, which means I can't use it again.\n\nThe problem is that the first script saved the response keys but then tried to access `creds_data['access_token']` which threw a KeyError. So the credentials file never got updated with the new tokens. I need to run a script that successfully saves the tokens, but I can't generate a new auth code without user interaction since the OAuth flow requires them to approve access again.\n\nLet me approach this differently - I could use the refresh token to get a new access token, or better yet, just re-run the full OAuth flow in the browser where the user approves access again and I capture a fresh auth code.\n","thinkingSignature":"da794ec9b01271b927f16cbad2856cc6705e412012f07e2f633a4a246ede597b"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nThe auth code was already consumed (one-time use). We need to do the flow again. Let me open a fresh consent page — watch for the redirect and tell me when you see it:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_36cenm1m950w_1","name":"browser","arguments":{"action":"navigate","targetId":"94B309987A1E0DBFAD8AB16C61DF6476","url":"https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/v2/auth?client_id=1038884317442-c84cvhcau9j76o8ej19jtnmig1lbc43s.app